{"questionId":"14509492","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A farmer is growing a field of rice plants. The height, <em>H</em> cm, of each plant can be modelled by a normal distribution with mean &mu; and standard deviation &sigma;.</p>\n<p>It is known that P(<em>H</em> &lt; 82.4) = 0.213 and P(<em>H</em> &gt; 87.3) = 0.409.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The farmer measures 100 randomly selected plants. Any plant with a height greater than 87.3 cm is considered ready to harvest. Heights of plants are independent of each other.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Given that fewer than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>44</mn></math> plants are ready to harvest, find the probability that exactly <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>32</mn></math> plants are ready to harvest.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>44</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>702975</mn><mo>…</mo></math>(seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>recognition of conditional probability&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note: </strong>recognition must be shown in context, either in symbols e.g.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn><mo> </mo><menclose notation=\"left\"><mo> </mo><mi>X</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>44</mn></menclose></mrow></mfenced></math>, or in words e.g.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>32</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>plants</mi><mo> </mo><menclose notation=\"left\"><mo> </mo><mi>less</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>than</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>44</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>plants</mi></menclose></mrow></mfenced></math>, not only as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo> </mo><menclose notation=\"left\"><mo> </mo><mi>B</mi></menclose></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><menclose notation=\"left\"><mo> </mo><mi>X</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>44</mn></menclose></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>44</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>43</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0157931</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>702975</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>(</strong><em><strong>A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0224661</mn><mo>…</mo></math></strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><menclose notation=\"right\"><mn>32</mn><mo> </mo></menclose><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>44</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0225</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"14509492","referenceCode":"23N.2.SL.TZ1.9cii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Given that fewer than 44 plants are ready to harvest, find the probability that exactly 32 plants are ready to harvest.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.8—Binomial distribution","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.11—Conditional and independent probabilities, test for independence"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
